"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90683","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>Information on Ministers’ meetings with external organisations is published quarterly on the Gov.uk site. This reflects the Government’s commitment to transparency. However, we cannot identify without incurring disproportionate cost every visit over the period for all Ministers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Relevant transparency reports can be found as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>1 January to 31 March 2013: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/212312/defra-min-transparency-1213-q4.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/212312/defra-min-transparency-1213-q4.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There has been a delay in publishing transparency data for 1 January to 31 March 2014. We expect it to be available shortly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>1 April to 30 June 2013:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/246396/Ministerial_expenses_-_1_April_to_30_June_2013.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/246396/Ministerial_expenses_-_1_April_to_30_June_2013.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>1 July to 30 September 2013:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/265462/Ministers_Quarterly_return_July_to_September_2013.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/265462/Ministers_Quarterly_return_July_to_September_2013.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>1 October to 31 December 2013:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/320333/Ministerial_Quarterly_Transparency_information_-_October_to_December_2013.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/320333/Ministerial_Quarterly_Transparency_information_-_October_to_December_2013.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-09-09T10:06:40.66047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90683/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90683/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-04","Domestic Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 18 June 2014, Official Report, columns 626-7W, on official visits, what domestic visits she and her predecessor have made since January 2013; and what the purpose of each such visit was.","false","Biography information for Sheila Gilmore","Edinburgh East","Sheila Gilmore","208297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90684","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p>Core Defra procures energy from the Crown Commercial Services Energy Frameworks. These pan-government contracts enable Defra to benefit from economies of scale and risk-managed procurement from the energy markets, so keeping costs down. Energy costs are also minimised through measures to reduce and improve the control of energy use in its buildings.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The biggest contributor to reduced energy costs has been the rationalisation of Defra’s estate. Since 2012/13 the Department has reduced its London estate from four to two properties, making more efficient use of space and reducing energy consumption as part of the overall strategy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Core Defra has also reduced energy costs by investing in voltage optimisation, more efficient heating systems, LED lighting and better insulation. Smart metering also enables Core Defra to monitor and target excessive consumption and ensure building systems are operating to optimum efficiency.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-09-11T16:15:03.1833292Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90684/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90684/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-04","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to reduce energy costs in her Department; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","208341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90685","Department of Health","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) advises that the set up and operating costs will be resourced from the FSA’s operating budget. The FSA has committed to a review of likely future needs after two years. The Elliott report estimates that the Food Crime Unit will cost between £2-4 million per year. It is too early to predict exact costs at this stage.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-09-09T14:28:33.2439324Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90685/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90685/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Food: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the written statement of 4 September 2014, on Elliott Review, what budget the Food Crime Unit will be allocated for (a) setting up and (b) operating in financial years (i) 2014-15 and (ii) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","208365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90686","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p>Food Integrity and Food Crime will be a cross-Government strategic group chaired by me. The group is being established to bring together departments with a shared interest in the integrity of the food chain, consumer protection and confidence in food, food surveillance and crime, with the purpose of strengthening the co-ordination of the Government’s activity in these areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Members of the group will be Government Ministers from the Department of Health, Business Innovations and Skills and the Home Office, and the Chairman of the Food Standards Agency. It will be supported by a cross-departmental group of senior officials chaired by the Permanent Secretary to Defra.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A date for the first meeting this autumn is being arranged. The Terms of Reference and full membership details will be available shortly.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-09-11T16:16:18.9483796Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90686/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90686/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-04","Food Integrity and Food Crime Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the written statement of 4 September 2014, on Elliott Review, which departments will be represented on that group and at what level of seniority; what the membership will be of that group; and when that group will meet; what the terms of reference are of the cross-government group on Food Integrity and Food Crime.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","208366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90687","Department of Health","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) advises that the Food Crime Unit is likely to include seconded police officers and other experts, as appropriate. The exact mix of background and skills has not been finalised. In addition to officers working within the Unit, the FSA will continue to work with an extensive network of law enforcement partners (including the police and Local Authorities) to access and draw on intelligence to task investigations and to build links internationally.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-09-09T14:29:38.0715542Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90687/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90687/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Food: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the written statement of 4 September 2014, on Elliott Review, how many police officers will work in the Food Crime Unit.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","208364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90688","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p>The Secretary of State has not discussed the recording of food crime as an identifiable category of crime in police databases with the Home Secretary.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-09-11T16:16:53.6714136Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90688/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90688/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-04","Food: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for the Home Department on enabling the recording of food crime as an identifiable category of crime in police databases.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","208354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90689","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>Professor Elliott estimates that the Food Crime Unit will cost between £2-4 million per year. The costs of a unit this size will be met within the Food Standards Agency’s (FSA) existing budgets, however it is too early to predict exact figures.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>No other budgets within the FSA will be cut and their core remit will remain food safety and consumer protection. Instead the FSA has used a recent restructuring exercise to bring together skills in intelligence and investigation and redirect them to resource the new Unit. The FSA is also bolstering its analytical and intelligence capability through recruitment and secondments from other agencies.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The FSA has committed to review likely future needs after two years. At this point there will also be further consideration of budgetary implications.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-09-09T16:26:59.5964851Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90689/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90689/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-04","Food: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to her written statement of 4 September 2014, on the Elliott Review, what extra resources (a) her Department and (b) the Government will provide to the Food Standards Agency for the establishment and operation of the Food Crime Unit in financial year (i) 2014-15 and (ii) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","208361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90690","Department of Health","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>The Food Standards Agency advises that the Food Crime Unit will be operational and the first phase will incorporate a well-developed intelligence capability by the end of 2014.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-09-09T14:38:44.0091641Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90690/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90690/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Food: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the written statement of 4 September 2014, on the Elliott Review, when the Food Crime Unit will be operational.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","208360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90691","Department of Health","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>The Food Standards Agency advises that it has already reorganised existing teams that deal with food incidents, fraud and intelligence to form the core of the new unit and is recruiting a small number of additional permanent and seconded staff to support this. This is likely to include seconded police officers and other experts, as appropriate. The exact mix of background and skills has not been finalised.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-09-09T14:26:37.4512566Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90691/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90691/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Food: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the written statement of 4 September 2014, on the Elliott Review, how many staff at each grade will be (a) recruited and (b) seconded to the Food Crime Unit.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","208362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90692","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-09-10","<p> </p><p>Defra and BIS have regular discussions on a range of skills development issues, including reform of apprenticeships, to ensure that different departmental programmes are complementary and can effectively support growth. The Apprenticeship Trailblazers have had a strong focus on the food industry, with schemes supporting food engineering and butchery skills. I fully support the skills and apprenticeship agenda and regularly discuss this with stakeholders in the food and farming sectors.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-09-10T14:11:08.8261717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90692/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90692/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-04","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she and Ministers in her Department have had with Ministers in the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills on the proposed reform of apprenticeships; what effect those discussions will have on her Department's projects and the work of their supply chain; and whether officials in her Department sit on programme boards managing the reform.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","208210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90693","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-09-10","<p> </p><p>Defra actively shares scientific information on bovine TB with the Department for Agriculture and Rural Development in Northern Ireland (DARDNI). Although Defra’s TB research budget does not cover Northern Ireland, DARDNI staff members regularly attend meetings of Defra’s TB Science Advisory Body sub-groups and Defra shares findings from its research with DARDNI including research on improving diagnostic tests for TB in badgers. The Chief Veterinary Officers of England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland, and senior policy officials, also meet monthly to discuss all issues related to bovine tuberculosis, including research findings.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-09-10T10:15:56.0790064Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90693/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90693/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-04","Bovine Tuberculosis: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to exchange scientific research with the Department of Agriculture in Northern Ireland on tackling bovine tuberculosis; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","208227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90694","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>The UK continues to raise its opposition to the Faroese cetacean hunts at every appropriate opportunity.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Most recently, in May 2014, the UK Commissioner to the International Whaling Commission (IWC) wrote to the Danish and Faroese governments to reiterate our concerns over the welfare and sustainability of their hunts. Prior to this, the UK Ambassador to Denmark visited the Faroe Islands in April 2014 and raised the issue in a meeting with the Prime Minister and officials from their Fisheries Ministry.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-09-09T12:57:18.889544Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90694/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90694/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-04","Cetaceans: Faroe Islands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions her Department has had with the government of Denmark about hunting cetaceans in the Faroe Islands.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","208168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90695","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-11","<p>We are closely monitoring the case of Abdulhadi Al Khawaja. As in the case of his 110 day hunger strike in 2012, we are concerned about his welfare. Bahraini Ministry of Interior’s Ombudsman’s Office announced it was launching an investigation into the conditions of his detention. As a result, an investigator visited Mr Al Khawaja in Jau prison. We understand that Mr Al Khawaja has seen medical staff regularly since he began his hunger strike and that, according to the Ombudsman’s Office, the medical staff continue to provide him with health care and are monitoring his medical condition closely.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-09-11T09:07:27.779977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90695/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90695/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Bahrain","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Bahraini counterpart on the detention of Abdulhadi Alkhawaja; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","208155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90696","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-11","<p>We are aware of the arrest of Maryam Al-Khawaja last week. We are monitoring the case closely. The British Ambassador to Bahrain raised her case with the Bahraini authorities last week. We urge the Government of Bahrain to ensure that due legal process is fully respected and international norms of justice adhered to.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-09-11T09:56:32.8453611Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90696/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90696/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Bahrain","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the government of Bahrain about the detention of Maryam Al-Khawaja at Bahrain International Airport; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","208156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90697","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-11","<p>Since January 2014, Egypt has held a constitutional referendum; elected a new President, Abdel Fattah Al Sisi; and is preparing for parliamentary elections. We look to President Al Sisi to take steps to implement the rights contained in Egypt’s constitution by opening up political space, in particular ensuring freedom of expression and association as well as ensuring that human and legal rights are fully upheld. I raised these issues with the Egyptian Assistant Foreign Minister for Europe during my visit to Cairo on 25 August.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-09-11T10:13:24.2914786Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90697/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90697/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Egypt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of progress with democratic reform in Egypt.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","208149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90698","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-11","<p>We have raised the treatment of the Rohingya in every one of our recent Ministerial contacts with the Burmese government.</p><p>The former Foreign Secretary, my Right Hon. Friend the member for Richmond (Yorks) ( Mr Hague), raised the situation in Rakhine State in a call with his Burmese counterpart, U Wunna Maung Lwin, in April. He called for the Burmese government to facilitate humanitarian assistance to all communities in the State. I also raised this issue with Khin Maung Soe, Burmese Minister for Electric Power in July, as well as with the Burmese Ambassador, whom I summoned in April to register my concerns. More recently, Minister of State for International Development, Mr Desmond Swayne, discussed Rakhine with Minister for the President’s Office, U Soe Thein in August.<br> <br>Our Ambassador and Embassy officials consistently discuss these concerns with representatives of the Burmese government.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-09-11T16:29:11.6194101Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90698/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90698/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Burma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Burmese government on their treatment of the Rohingya.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","208152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90699","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-11","<p>Our assessment is that rockets are brought to Gaza from several sources, including the tunnels which run into the territory.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-09-11T11:54:46.1488585Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90699/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90699/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Hamas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the sources of rockets supplied to Hamas operating in Gaza; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","208182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90700","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-10","<p>We remain deeply concerned about the ability of terrorist groups in Iraq and Syria to acquire weapons and commit atrocities.<br> <br>The Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) has obtained its weaponry from a variety of sources, including by capturing them from Iraqi and Syrian security forces. Many of ISIL's supply needs are financed by its sale of oil and by money stolen during its advances in recent months.</p><p>We have emphasised the need to intensify efforts to stem the flow of weapons and fighters to extremist groups, including ISIL. Hundreds of foreigners are fighting with ISIL, gaining combat experience and potentially forging connections with other extremists. As part of its strategy to combat ISIL, the UK led work on UN Security Council Resolution 2170, adopted on 15 August, which condemns ISIL, Al Nusra Front (ANF) and other terrorist groups listed under Al Qaida sanctions. The resolution urges members to take measures to choke off recruitment and to target the growing phenomenon of foreign terrorist fighters and ISIL's sources of finance.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-09-10T14:51:51.7735903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90700/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90700/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on the sources of supply to Islamic State militants of their weapons and training; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","208183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90701","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-11","<p>The UK has been very active over the years of the Syria conflict, and it remains a top priority. The rise of the Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) threatens the UK, and the whole region.</p><p>With our international partners, we have focused on support for those pushing for an inclusive political settlement. This has led to our political and non-lethal assistance to moderate opposition groups. We have committed £30 million this financial year for helping the moderate opposition and bolstering regional resilience. We have given strong backing for UN efforts in the political track.</p><p>The UK has also focussed on holding Assad to account for his war crimes, which have included routine, indiscriminate bombardment of civilian areas, the use of chemical weapons, and the use of siege and surrender tactics. The UK is also the second largest bilateral humanitarian aid donor, and has been at the forefront of efforts in the UN Security Council to ensure aid gets to all those who need it.</p><p>The UK recently committed to tackling the threat from extremists, including ISIL. This needs a coordinated strategy in Syria and Iraq, and close coordination with the US and other partners.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-09-11T11:52:31.1468933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90701/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90701/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking with his international counterparts to stop the war in Syria; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","208184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90702","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-11","<p>As of 29 August, all of Syria’s declared chemical stockpile of 1,309.8 metric tonnes had been removed from Syria and thus put beyond use of the regime. 95.8%, or 1,254.8 metric tonnes had been destroyed either by incineration or neutralisation, including all of the Category 1 chemicals (those deemed most proliferation sensitive by the OPCW, plus isopropanol).</p><p>The destruction of some of the category 1 chemicals in the UK was completed on 5 August, three weeks after the arrival of the chemicals in the UK. A smaller quantity of Hydrogen Fluoride (a category 2 chemical) will be destroyed in the UK at the turn of the year. Other chemicals are being destroyed in Germany, Finland and the United States.</p><p>Syria was required to declare and destroy all stocks of chemical weapons and their precursors, and the facilities and equipment with which they were manufactured. The international community cannot have confidence that Syria’s declarations were complete while credible reports of the use of chemical weapons, such as chlorine, continue, and until all outstanding questions surrounding the declarations have been resolved. The OPCW continues to seek answers to a number of questions.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-09-11T09:22:27.9024413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90702/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90702/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much of Syria's chemical weapons arsenal (a) is intact and (b) has been destroyed to date; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","208185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90703","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-10","The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has records of 143 diplomats posted to the Embassy of the Russian Federation in London. In accordance with the Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations 1961, the Government grants immunity to diplomats posted to the Embassy of the Russian Federation according to their status.","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2014-09-10T14:51:41.8844691Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90703/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90703/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many Russian diplomats are serving with so-called diplomatic immunity in the Russian Embassy in London; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","208186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90704","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-09","<p>The situation in Ukraine remains of very grave concern to the UK, and Russia’s actions have presented the most serious security crisis in Europe since the end of the Cold War. With international partners we have unreservedly condemned all illegal interventions by Russia in Ukraine. In particular, the UK does not, and will not, recognise the illegal annexation of Crimea by Russia. This violates the UN Charter, is illegal under international law and breaches the commitments Russia made in the Budapest Memorandum. That is why Russia has been isolated in the Security Council and in the wider international community. We have, as required under the the terms of the memorandum, consulted the US frequently since the occupation and annexation of Crimea and destabilisation of the east by Russian-backed separatists. Both the US and UK continue to ensure that Russia pays a price through sanctions for the annexation of Crimea and its incursion into south-eastern Ukraine; we will maintain our pressure on Russia to use its influence to de-escalate the situation in the east.</p><p>The Budapest Memorandum does not specify any military commitments. In this Memorandum, in return for Ukraine giving up its nuclear weapons, Russia joined the UK and US in reaffirming their obligation to “refrain from the threat or use of force against the territorial integrity or political independence of Ukraine, and that none of their weapons will ever be used against Ukraine except in self-defence or otherwise in accordance with the Charter of the United Nations.” Russia is in clear breach of those commitments as well as a number of other international obligations and commitments, including under the UN Charter and the OSCE Helsinki Final Act.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-09-09T16:06:15.7063155Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90704/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90704/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Ukraine: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of whether the actions of the Russian Federation in relation to Ukraine are compliant with the provisions of the Budapest Memorandum on Security Assurances.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","208218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90705","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-11","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s engagement in Sudan does not include direct support to the demobilisation and integration of former Beja Congress fighters into civil or military roles.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2014-09-11T13:13:26.2659577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90705/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90705/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Sudan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the demobilisation and integration of former Beja Congress fighters into civil and military services is adequately supported.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","208189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90706","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-11","<p>The British Government continues to monitor Sudan’s National Dialogue process closely, including via regular reporting from its Embassy in Khartoum. We continue to call on the Government of Sudan to live up to its commitment to hold an inclusive national dialogue as the best way of achieving sustainable peace and a prosperous Sudan</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2014-09-11T13:10:51.247122Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90706/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90706/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Sudan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received of recent developments in Sudan's National Dialogue process.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","208190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90707","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-09","<p>We welcome the passing of the UN Human Rights Council resolution on Sri Lanka on 27 March, which established an international investigation into alleged violations and abuses of international law on both sides of the military conflict in Sri Lanka, in addition to calling for progress on human rights and reconciliation. The UK was a main co-sponsor of the resolution and will continue to give full support to the Office of UN High Commissioner for Human Rights (OHCHR) in establishing an international investigation, as mandated by the UN Human Rights Council.</p><p>The UN resolution calls upon the Sri Lankan government to co-operate with the OHCHR in the implementation of the resolution. We continue to urge the Sri Lankan government to co-operate with the OHCHR, and to view the international investigation as an opportunity to address the grievances of the past in the spirit of lasting peace and reconciliation. We also continue to call for the Commonwealth Ministerial Action Group, and the Commonwealth Secretary-General, to use their leverage to encourage Sri Lanka’s co-operation.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-09-09T10:51:51.97905Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90707/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90707/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Sri Lanka","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he plans to take through the Commonwealth and UN to secure Sri Lanka's compliance with the UN Human Rights Committee's resolution on the war crimes and civil rights investigation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","208355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90708","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-11","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) is committed to meeting the Greener Government Commitments and to reducing the energy use of its operations. In 2014/15, the FCO will be undertaking the following measures to reduce the energy costs of its UK operations: installing additional LED lighting; installing additional daylight and motion sensors on lighting; improvements to equipment and operation of the heating infrastructure in the King Charles Street main building; virtualising and consolidating the server estate in our main data-centre; adjustments and interventions to reduce the cooling requirement of its main data-centre; and installing additional automated meter reading and more efficient pumps. Consolidation of the FCO’s principal London offices into one building in 2015 will also bring large net energy savings.</p><p>The energy savings from these measures in 2014/15 will add to numerous energy saving initiatives in recent years such as installation of voltage regulation equipment and thermostatic radiator valves; LED lighting; decommissioning legacy IT systems; powering down desktops at night and staff switch off campaigns.</p><p>In addition the FCO enjoys the benefits of utilising the centralised Government Procurement service framework for the purchasing of its electricity and gas.</p><p>The answer relates to the FCO's UK Estate, which comprises King Charles St, Old Admiralty Building, Lancaster House, Carlton Gardens, Hanslope Park and Northgate House. It would incur a disproportionate cost to source this information from our network of overseas Posts, as this information is held locally.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-09-11T14:27:41.4357398Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90708/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90708/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to reduce energy costs in his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","208342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90709","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-10","<p>Foreign Office salaries are determined by a range of factors including grade of the person, performance and length of time in employment. <br>Details of our salary ranges can be found through the Data.gov.uk website on the FCO staff and salary data pages, and details of our highest paid staff can be found in the FCO Annual accounts in the Remuneration section on page 63 in the 2013-2014 accounts. All FCO staff who earn more than 150,000 are also published by Cabinet Office on the Gov.uk &quot;high earners” pages.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-09-10T14:56:31.0650172Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90709/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90709/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-04","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the (a) highest and (b) lowest full-time equivalent salary paid by (i) his Department and (ii) its public bodies was in (A) 2010-11, (B) 2011-12, (C) 2012-13, (D) 2013-14 and (E) 2014-15; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Mr Gareth Thomas","208283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90710","Department of Health","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p>Data on the proportion of people over the age of 65 diagnosed with dementia after being admitted to hospital as an emergency inpatient in England in each year since 2009 is not available as we are unable to determine whether a patient was diagnosed after being admitted to hospital including British sign language users.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","208266","2014-09-11T10:17:54.5787734Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90710/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90710/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of people over the age of 65 were diagnosed with dementia after being admitted to hospital as an emergency inpatient in England in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","208265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90711","Department of Health","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p>Data on the proportion of people over the age of 65 who presented themselves to a clinician showing key symptoms of dementia in 2013 and 2014 to date is not centrally held.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-09-11T10:14:21.7419733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90711/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90711/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of people over the age of 65 presented themselves to a clinician showing key symptoms of dementia in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","208264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90712","Department of Health","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p>Data on how much the National Health Service has spent on specialist assessment and diagnosis services for deaf people including British sign language users with dementia is not available. However the NHS is advised that it is good clinical practice to take into account a person’s general health, including their hearing, when people are investigated and treated for dementia.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-09-11T10:19:10.1164809Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90712/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90712/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the NHS spent on specialist assessment and diagnostic services for deaf British Sign Language users with dementia in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","208269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90713","Department of Health","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p>Figures on how much the National Health Service spent on dementia assessment for diagnostic purposes in each year since 2010 is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-09-11T13:04:11.1390693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90713/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90713/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the NHS spent on dementia assessment for diagnostic purposes in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","208270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90714","Department of Health","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p>Data on the proportion of people over the age of 65 diagnosed with dementia after being admitted to hospital as an emergency inpatient in England in each year since 2009 is not available as we are unable to determine whether a patient was diagnosed after being admitted to hospital including British sign language users.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","208265","2014-09-11T10:17:55.1593378Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90714/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90714/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many deaf British Sign Language users over the age of 65 were diagnosed with dementia after being admitted to hospital as an emergency inpatient in England in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","208266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90715","Department of Health","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p>Experiments on animals have been performed over a number of years with the first successful pronuclear transfer (PNT) technique performed in mice in 1983 by McGrath and Solter. Maternal spindle transfer (MST) is a technique developed in the United States of America in 2009 and has been performed successfully in mice, non-human primates, as well as in sheep and cows. Research on both MST and PNT has been carried out successfully on human embryos. On-going studies of PNT and MST continue to be carried out on mice in the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>An extensive review of the safety and efficacy of MST and PNT to prevent mitochondrial disease was completed by the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority’s Expert Scientific Panel, which includes detailed consideration of animal model studies and can be found on their website:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>www.hfea.gov.uk/docs/Third_Mitochondrial_replacement_scientific_review.pdf</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2014-09-11T14:02:52.9570435Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90715/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90715/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Animal Experiments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of tests on animals conducted in the UK using mitochondrial replacement techniques in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","208267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90716","Department of Health","false","2014-09-10","<p> </p><p>In line with data protection legislation, the salary information in both the tables attached is provided as salary ranges, in order to avoid disclosing personal information.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-09-10T13:32:46.9639736Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90716/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90716/answer","PQ208285 - Table.docx","PQ208285 - Table.docx","Tables","Tables","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90716/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the (a) highest and (b) lowest full-time equivalent salary paid by (i) his Department and (ii) its public bodies was in (A) 2010-11, (B) 2011-12, (C) 2012-13, (D) 2013-14 and (E) 2014-15; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Mr Gareth Thomas","208285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90717","Department of Health","false","2014-09-10","<p> </p><p>There are currently no plans to institute an awards scheme to recognise best practice among doctors who deliver training to medical students. However, the General Medical Council has established a phased process for implementing arrangements for recognising trainers in medical training. All trainers in four specific roles will be fully recognised by 31 July 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The arrangements relate to:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>- named educational supervisors in postgraduate training;</p><p> </p><p>- named clinical supervisors in postgraduate training;</p><p> </p><p>- lead coordinators of undergraduate training at each local education provider; and</p><p> </p><p>- doctors responsible for overseeing students’ educational progress for each medical school.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-09-10T13:02:23.1179599Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90717/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90717/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Medicine: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will institute an awards scheme to recognise best practice among doctors who deliver training to medical students.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","208322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90718","Department of Health","false","2014-09-09","<p>Health Education England (HEE) is the special health authority established by the Government to promote high quality education and training for the current and future National Health Service workforce backed by a near £5 billion annual budget.</p><p>HEE have advised that responsibility for the development and organisation of placements for undergraduate medical students rests with individual medical schools, including those placements in GP practices. These are all negotiated locally to ensure high quality education programmes. HEE supports moves to increase opportunities for more students and trainees to obtain experience in GP practices.</p><p>Additionally, HEE has been mandated to ensure that 50% of trainees completing foundation level training enter GP training programmes by 2016.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-09-09T15:01:07.0108013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90718/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90718/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Medicine: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to increase the number of places for medical students to undertake training in GP practices.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","208308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90719","Department of Health","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>NHS England has advised a reply to the hon Member’s letter of 7 July 2014 was issued on the 8 September 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has also advised the NHS Central Midlands Commissioning Support Unit has sought consent from the hon Member’s constituent to investigate the concerns regarding the level of care received; they are awaiting a response.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-09-09T14:31:25.5483857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90719/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90719/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will arrange for a reply to be sent to the letter concerning a constituent sent by the hon Member for Walsall North to the Walsall Clinical Commissioning Group on 7 July 2014, which was sent on to NHS England Patient Experience Team in West Bromwich; and if he will inquire into the reasons for the time taken to send a substantive reply to that letter.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","208177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90720","Department of Health","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p>The Department has had discussions with their counterparts at the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) on the development of a higher apprenticeship for nursing. Aside from this, the Department has had no other specific discussions with BIS on the subject of apprenticeship reforms in general. However, the Department of Health will be implementing the Civil Service Fast Track Apprenticeship Scheme (CSFTAS) in October 2014. This scheme was commissioned by the Minister for the Cabinet Office and the Head of the Civil Service in October 2012. It is a cross-Government corporate scheme that sits alongside and complements the Civil Service Fast Stream Programme as another talent strand. As this is a cross-Government scheme, BIS would have been directly involved in this initiative.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Managing future talent is a positive aim under the Civil Service Reform Plan and is a key enabler of organisation effectiveness and future delivery of our business.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The CSFTAS demonstrates the Civil Service’s commitment to providing high quality opportunities for young people.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department is also working with Cabinet Office colleagues in developing a commercial apprenticeship programme for the civil service.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-09-11T15:52:10.8883789Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90720/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90720/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he and Ministers in his Department have had with Ministers in the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills on the proposed reform of apprenticeships; what effect those discussions will have on his Department's projects and the work of their supply chain; and whether officials in his Department sit on programme boards managing the reform.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","208211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90721","Department of Health","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>The latest GP Patient Survey (GPPS) results were published on 3 July 2014 and can be found on the GPPS website:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>https://gp-patient.co.uk/</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The data included in the July publication was collected in two waves during July to September 2013 and January to March 2014.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-09-09T14:40:13.192294Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90721/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90721/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when his Department will publish the results of the GP patient survey conducted on behalf of NHS England by Ipsos MORI.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","208255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90722","Department of Health","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>The survey was sent to 2.63 million patients. There was a 34% response rate to the survey, with 903,357 surveys being returned.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-09-09T14:42:25.3670084Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90722/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90722/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients (a) were invited to participate in and (b) responded to the recent GP patient survey.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","208254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90723","Department of Health","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>The business case referred to in the answer given on 2 August 2014 is the General Dental Council’s (GDC) consultation document setting out the GDC’s rationale for the proposed fee rise. The consultation closed on 4 September 2014 and the document is available at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>www.gdc-uk.org/GDCcalendar/Consultations/Pages/Consultation-on-the-Annual-Retention-Fee-(ARF)-Level-for-2015.aspx</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The GDC is an independent body and therefore neither the Department nor The Professional Standards Authority for Health and Social Care as a formal role in reviewing the GDC’s case. However, in my role as Parliamentary Under Secretary for Health, on 3 September 2014 I met with the GDC where this issue was discussed.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Each year the Care Quality Commission (CQC) consults on its proposed fee structure for the following year. The CQC intends to publish a consultation on its proposed fee structure for 2015-16 and draft impact assessment in the next month. The final impact assessment will be published in 2015. These documents will be available on the CQC’s website. Following consultation, the CQC will present its proposals to my Rt. Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-09-09T14:48:44.0749716Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90723/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90723/answer","PQ208258 - Hansard Extract.docx","PQ208258 - Hansard Extract.docx","Hansard Extract","Hansard Extract","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90723/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-04","General Dental Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 2 September 2014, Official Report, on the General Dental Council, if (a) his Department and (b) the Professional Standards Authority For Health and Social Care will publish its review of the business case for the increase in years charged by the General Dental Council; and if similar reviews will be published of the Care Quality Commission increase in fees to dental professionals.","true","Biography information for Sir Paul Beresford","Mole Valley","Sir Paul Beresford","208258"
